# Line-ending insurance for a Windows + WSL project.
#
# Background: Windows ends text lines with two characters (CRLF, "\r\n");
# Linux uses one (LF, "\n"). If a shell script picks up Windows endings,
# Linux sees a stray "\r" glued to every line and bash fails with the
# infamous "bad interpreter: /bin/bash^M" error.
#
# These rules tell git to ALWAYS store and check out shell scripts (and
# text generally) with LF endings, so scripts written on Windows run
# perfectly inside WSL. This overrides any local core.autocrlf setting.

* text=auto eol=lf
*.sh text eol=lf
*.md text eol=lf

# Binary files: never touch their bytes.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.ico binary
